2. What Is a Set?

A Set is a collection of unique values. Adding a value that already exists does nothing вҖ” the Set simply ignores it. Like Map, Set remembers insertion order.

Creating and Using a Set

const set = new Set();
set.add("apple");
set.add("banana");
set.add("cherry");
set.add("apple"); // duplicate вҖ” silently ignored
console.log(set.size); // 3, not 4
console.log(set.has("banana")); // true
console.log(set.has("mango")); // false
set.delete("banana");
console.log(set.size); // 2

Enter fullscreen mode

Exit fullscreen mode

The Uniqueness Property in Action

This is Set's defining characteristic. No matter how many times you add the same value, it appears exactly once:

const tags = new Set();
// Simulating tags being added from multiple places
tags.add("javascript");
tags.add("nodejs");
tags.add("javascript"); // already there вҖ” no-op
tags.add("webdev");
tags.add("nodejs"); // already there вҖ” no-op
tags.add("javascript"); // already there вҖ” no-op
console.log([...tags]); // ["javascript", "nodejs", "webdev"]
console.log(tags.size); // 3

